        <body>       
                 
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>450 W. Randolph St.<lb/>
                July 11. 1887<lb/></p>
            <p>Dr. S. Morais&#44; Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>This forenoon the letter&#45;carrier brought me your est&#39;d<lb/> letter dated July 8.&#44; and this afternoon your postal card<lb/> of the 9. inst. came.  Thanks for both&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>This forenoon already I mailed some more of my<lb/> &#34;miscellanies&#34; to Mr. Peixotto.  I made&#44; with your<lb/> permission&#44; copious extracts from your former letter<lb/> and added some remarks to them.<lb/></p>
            <p>I took it for granted that your reference to &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93; &#167; 537&#34;<lb/> was either a slip of the pen or a failing of the memory<lb/> for a moment.  And so I corrected it&#44; in extracting the<lb/> passage&#44; by substituting &#34;557&#34; for &#34;537&#34;.<lb/></p>
            <p>In a postscript to your letter received to day you<lb/> come to say something upon uncommon names in use among<lb/> Italian &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Among these names you mention one by the name<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I know of another and more renowned<lb/> &#34;Abiad Sar Shalom&#34;.  The author of the book &#91;Hebrew&#93; was<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>a certain Rabbi in Mantua whose name was &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44;<lb/> and who lived in the beginning of the 18. century.<lb/>  In Lampronti&#39;s &#91;Hebrew&#93; many &#91;Hebrew&#93; from him are<lb/> to be met with.  I have those volumes of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> which were published within recent years&#44; and so I met<lb/> often that remarkable name &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Some interesting<lb/> biographical notes about this Mantuan &#91;Hebrew&#93; are to be<lb/> found in M. S. Ghirondi&#39;s &#91;Hebrew&#93; on pp. 36 &#38; 39.<lb/>  Azulai in his &#91;Hebrew&#93; also mentions this Rabbi and<lb/> speaks with great respect of him.<lb/></p>
            <p>In esteem and in friendship&#44; I remain&#44; dear sir&#44;<lb/>
                yours very truly<lb/>
                B. Felsenthal.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>A few days ago I received from Is. Gr&#228;ber&#44; Jaroslau&#44; a<lb/> copy of the &#91;Hebrew&#93; which he published.  Thus far I have not<lb/> found the time to read anything therein except your &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#40;Is a sonnet called in Hebrew &#91;Hebrew&#93; on account of its 14<lb/> lines&#44; &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;&#41;  I need not say anything in praise<lb/> of your mastery of the language&#59; I knew this long ago that you can<lb/> write Hebrew elegantly.  But as to your joyful looking forward to a<lb/> brilliant future of the Hebrew language&#44;&#45;&#45;dear Dr.&#44; you are too sanguine&#33;  I<lb/> am rather&#44; in this respect&#44; entertaining pessimistic views.  F.<lb/></p>
            </body>
